three-year term Jan 1778","notes":"Enlisted age 18. Reported sick in general hospital Dec 1776. Later served at Fort George.","war_id":"WAR004"}],"bio":{"display_name":"Doctor Joseph Taft","title":"Doctor","first_name":"Joseph","last_name":"Taft","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST002","relationship":"alumnus"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"military","header":"Continental Line fifer at eighteen, three engagements","body":"Joseph Taft enlisted on January 1, 1776 at age eighteen as a fifer in Captain Silas Wild's company of Colonel Edmund Phinney's regiment of the Continental Line. He reengaged in November 1776 under Colonel Brewer and signed a three-year term in January 1778, with later service at Fort George on Lake George. He had been reported sick in the general hospital in December 1776 — a common fate of soldiers in the smallpox-stricken winter camps of the war's second year."},{"number":2,"category":"career","header":"Postwar Harvard, then physician at Weston","body":"After three years in the Continental Army, Taft returned to Massachusetts and entered Harvard College — graduating in 1783, the year of the Treaty of Paris that closed the war. He practiced as a physician at Weston Massachusetts for the rest of his working life and died at Randolph Massachusetts in January 1824 at age sixty-six."}],"slug":"joseph-taft-1757"},"HD0311":{"id":"HD0311","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"generation_from_thomas":6,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1759,"month":2,"day":20,"city":"Braintree","state":"Massachusetts"},"parents":{"father_id":"I00112","mother_id":"H00218"},"tags":[],"sources":[],"gender":"fem